{"id": "duc04-testb-26:3#10", "contents": "The idea for a Truth Commission emerged as a compromise during the negotiations that brought about South Africa's peaceful transition from a white supremacist state to a non-racial democracy. However, only about 250 former police officers came forward to testify, most of them low-ranking officials. High-ranking officials, such as former President P.W. Botha and former Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok, have not applied for amnesty. The commission's report holds these individuals responsible for gross human rights violations. The ANC is also facing the possibility of prosecuting its own members, including Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, who is accused of taking part in assaults and abductions."}
